{'entities': [{'id': 242192, 'name': 'Error 9006', 'description': 'Error 9006 occurs when the GC life time is shorter than the transaction duration, potentially leading to data deletion.'}, {'id': 900571, 'name': 'tidb_gc_life_time', 'description': "The 'tidb_gc_ life_ time' is a TiDB system variable that controls the retention time of historical data before it is garbage collected. It determines how long deleted or updated data versions are retained, preventing premature deletion during operations like large data exports and imports. The default value varies between 10 minutes (10m0s) and 30 minutes (30m), depending on the source. Increasing this variable can prevent data loss during replication tasks but may also increase storage usage and impact performance, especially for range queries. It is crucial to set this value longer than the total time of data export/import and sink creation to avoid issues with old snapshots being garbage collected. This variable was introduced in TiDB v5.0 and has a global scope."}, {'id': 242203, 'name': 'Error 9001', 'description': 'Error 9001 occurs when TiDB fails to access PD due to timeout or network issues.'}, {'id': 242206, 'name': 'PD server', 'description': "The PD (Placement Driver) server is a critical component in TiDB, responsible for managing the cluster's metadata and scheduling. It ensures data distribution across TiKV nodes and handles region splits and merges. When TiDB fails to access the PD server due to timeout, it triggers Error 9001. This error typically occurs when there are network issues between TiDB and PD or if the PD server's disk is slow and busy."}, {'id': 270039, 'name': 'Error Number 9002', 'description': 'TiKV server timeout error, indicating a timeout in the TiKV request.'}, {'id': 420064, 'name': 'TiKV Server', 'description': 'TiKV Server is a distributed transactional key-value storage engine used in the TiDB cluster. It serves as the key-value storage layer, providing a distributed storage engine for data persistence and processing. TiKV is responsible for storing data in regions and supports distributed transactions at the key-value pair level. It ensures data persistence, maintains high availability with multiple replicas (three by default), and supports automatic failover. TiKV operates under Snapshot Isolation and is a critical component of the TiDB ecosystem. It functions as the storage engine within TiDB, responsible for storing actual data.'}, {'id': 242196, 'name': 'Error 9008', 'description': 'Error 9008 occurs when too many requests are sent to TiKV, exceeding the limit.'}, {'id': 900116, 'name': 'Error 9007', 'description': '`Write conflict` error in TiDB, typically caused by multiple transactions modifying the same row of data when using optimistic transaction mode. This issue often arises due to concurrent modifications and can be addressed by retrying at the application level or reviewing schema design and data access patterns.'}, {'id': 900469, 'name': 'Write Conflict', 'description': "A write conflict occurs when two or more transactions attempt to modify the same data concurrently, potentially leading to data inconsistency if not properly managed. In optimistic transactions, write conflicts are detected during the commit phase, triggering a rollback and retry mechanism. Pessimistic transactions prevent write conflicts by locking resources, while optimistic transactions handle them through retries. Write conflicts can also occur in autocommit transactions. Common scenarios include concurrent updates to a database table, such as modifying book stock, which can lead to errors like Error 8002 and Error 9007. In TiDB's optimistic transaction model, during the prewrite stage of 2PC, if two transactions attempt to write to the same key concurrently, the transaction with the later start timestamp will encounter a write conflict."}, {'id': 242195, 'name': 'Error 9007', 'description': 'Error 9007 is a write conflict error that occurs in pessimistic transactions with unique index conflicts.'}, {'id': 270043, 'name': 'Error Number 9003', 'description': 'TiKV Server is Busy error, usually occurring when the workload is too high.'}], 'relationships': [{'id': 241962, 'relationship': 'Error 9006 can be resolved by adjusting the tidb_gc_life_time variable.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/error-codes', 'source_entity': {'id': 242192, 'name': 'Error 9006'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 900571, 'name': 'tidb_gc_life_time'}}, {'id': 241979, 'relationship': 'Error 9001 occurs when TiDB fails to access the PD server due to timeout.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/error-codes', 'source_entity': {'id': 242203, 'name': 'Error 9001'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 242206, 'name': 'PD server'}}, {'id': 270086, 'relationship': 'Error Number 9002 indicates a timeout in the TiKV server request.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/error-codes', 'source_entity': {'id': 270039, 'name': 'Error Number 9002'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 420064, 'name': 'TiKV Server'}}, {'id': 241967, 'relationship': 'Error 9008 occurs when too many requests are sent to the TiKV server.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/error-codes', 'source_entity': {'id': 242196, 'name': 'Error 9008'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 420064, 'name': 'TiKV Server'}}, {'id': 92835, 'relationship': 'Error 9007 indicates a write conflict.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidbcloud/dev-guide-transaction-troubleshoot', 'source_entity': {'id': 900116, 'name': 'Error 9007'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 900469, 'name': 'Write Conflict'}}, {'id': 241964, 'relationship': 'Error 9007 involves a write conflict on a unique index in TiKV.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/error-codes', 'source_entity': {'id': 242195, 'name': 'Error 9007'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 420064, 'name': 'TiKV Server'}}, {'id': 270087, 'relationship': 'Error Number 9003 occurs when the TiKV server is busy.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/error-codes', 'source_entity': {'id': 270043, 'name': 'Error Number 9003'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 420064, 'name': 'TiKV Server'}}]}

